title: For Sale/Trade:  1880 Enfield Martini Rifle
postcontent:
Picked this up while deployed to Afghanistan.  Wanted one of the Khyber Pass Enfield knock-offs as a souvenir.  When I got back and started doing some research it seems this is not a knock off but a real one.  "Enfield" was spelled correctly and I couldn't find any of the typo's, mis-marks or other details normally hosed up on the knock-offs.
577/450 caliber, I have two rounds for it that will go with it.
Needless to say, I haven't fired it and would never consider doing so unless a gunsmith said it was good to go.  Picked up the rounds to display with the rifle.    

Neat rifle for the time, though my shoulder aches at the thought of firing it.  Pretty good condition all things considered.

Obviously you need to make your own assessment on this - heck, I thought I was buying a knock off.  So I really am in no position to make definitive representations.  And a real Enfield doesn't carry the same sentiment for me that an Afghan knock-off would have, so I am looking to clear out some safe space or trade.  

Thanks for taking the time to look.

title: For Sale:  2 Remington Model 11 For Sale
postcontent:
I have two Remington Model 11 for sale. I would consider some trades, but mainly looking for cash. They're not in flawless condition, but since one was made in 1922, it's kind of expected. Let's face it, John Browning designed these things to last. These two guns have been in the family a number of years and it's time to find them a new home. 

Serial# 7212XX

Made in 1945 (barrel code dated), 2 3/4" 12 Ga. w/ modified barrel, Sportster model. This gun is in fair shape. Most of the bluing is intact and the scroll work is in great condition. Downside, there's some rust and some wear on the stock. In good working order otherwise. I will take somewhat less for this gun than the one below.

Serial# 2424XX

Made in 1922 (serial number dated). 2 3/4" 12 Ga. w/full barrel. This gun is the older of the two and is in better condition. That said, it's bluing is probably about 85%. No rust, some small dings, but in good working order. Considering the thing in 91-years old, I'd say it was built to last. This has the old saftey (inside the trigger guard), which some refer to as a "suicide safety" so, I'd probably keep my finger off the trigger. The barrel isn't original and was made in 1945 (barrel code dated). Also, some joker in my family installed some gel recoil pad that exploded. I uninstalled that thing, but didn't put a new one on. Original screws are in the butt.  If you want this gun, you're going to have to make a good offer.

If a good buyer wants both we'll come to a good arrangement. 

If you're interested in one and not the other, state the serial number in the email. 

If you're confused about the pictures, the one with the scroll work is the 7212XX.

The market looks to be pretty firm at $300, but I am reasonable man.
